Project 4 : Term Deposit Sale¶

Submitted by Aman Kumar Agarwal¶

Question :¶

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to access if the product (bank term deposit) would be ('yes') or not ('no') subscribed.

The classification goal is to predict if the client will subscribe (yes/no) a term deposit (variable y).

Dataset : https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Bank+Marketing¶

Attribute Information¶

Input variables:¶

Bank client data:¶

1 - Age :Age of customer
2 - Job : type of Job
3 - Marital : Marital status
4 - Education : Educational Tier
5 - Default: Has credit in default?
6 - Balance: Average yearly balance. (in euros)
7 - Housing: Has housing loan?
8 - Loan: Has personal loan?

Related with the last contact of the current campaign:¶

9 - Contact: Contact communication type (unknown,telephone,cellular)
10 - Day: Last contact day of the month
11 - Month: Last contact month of year
12 - Duration: Last contact duration (in seconds)

Other attributes:¶

13 - Campaign: Number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client.
14 - Pdays: Number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign.
15 - Previous: Number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client.
16 - Poutcome: Outcome of the previous marketing campaign (unknown,other,failure,success)

Output variable¶

17 - y : has the client subscribed a term deposit? (yes,no)

5. Standardizing using Z score.¶

We see that the data contains values which are numerically very different. In balance we have values ranging from -8000 to +10000 whereas in other numerical columns, the values are 0 to 1. So these numerical differences make our model vulnerable to bias. Therefore standardizing the entire data using a standardization technique such as zscore is used.

-----------------------------------------Support Vector Machine--------------------------------------------¶

Creating a subset of the original data to train the support vector machine model.¶

Since Support Vector Machines (SVMs) are highly computationally intensive algorithms, a smaller subset of data, with 3000 values out of 45211 values is made. This enables the algorithm to run faster and helps to improve with a smaller dataset.

Conclusions¶

Insights from EDA¶

  1. There is no missing data in the available dataset.
  2. Attributes such as Balance, Duration and pdays have very high variance.
  3. Right skewness and presence of long right tails in Age attribute.
  4. Maximum customers lie between the age group 30-50
  5. People have been contacted mostly 1-10 times but it goes as high as 58. This can be due to any special needs of the customer.
  6. Most of the poeple from the previous campaign (81%) have not been contacted in this campaign. The bank should try and contact more of those customers.
  7. People belonging to the Low and medium balance groups have higher subscription rate.
  8. Most of the customers belong to the secondary education tier.
  9. Most of the customers do not have credit default.
  10. Maximum number of people in the previous campaign were contacted in the month of May (30.4%) followed by july (15.3%) and August(13.81%)
  11. Both divorcee and married people have higher chance of subscribing to term deposit than single people. This can be used to target in campaign.
  12. Most of the jobs are blue-collar jobs followed by management and technician.
  13. Primary education exists most in the higher age group bracekt between 40-60. The chances of customer subscribing to term deposit is higher in this group. This can be used to target in campaign.
  14. Most customers who were a success in previous campaign are also a success in this campaign. Therefore bank should target these customers first.
  15. People with high balance have low duration of calls, which makes sense as people with less balance are more likely to be interested in security term deposits.
  16. Clients who have been contacted between 1-20 times have subscribe most to term deposit. Therefore the bank should try avoiding the customers with very high number of contacts done with them and they have not subscribed.
  17. Duration is one of the most important attributes but it is not used in model building as in a real life scenario, if the duration of the call is known, then at the end the result will be known anyhow. Duration is therefore used only for benchmarking purpose.
  18. The customers with higher duration have a very high chance of subscribing to the term deposits.
  19. March is the only month where subscribing term deposit customers is higher than non-subscribing term deposits.
  20. The bank should try and target its customers most in the month of march as it shows the most promising nature for a cutomer to subscribe to the term deposit.

Model Inferences¶

  1. The logistic Regression model gives an accuracy score of 89%
  2. The Naive model gives an accuracy score of 81.23%
  3. The K Nearest Neighbours model gives an accuracy score of 89.07%
  4. The Support Vector Machine model gives an accuracy score of :89.31%(rbf), 88.24%(linear) and 81%(sigmoid)
  5. The Decision Tree model gives an accuracy score of 89.27%
  6. The Random Forest model gives an accuracy score of 89.25%
  7. Bagging showed the improvement in overall scores of Logistic regression, Naive Bayes, Support Vector Machine(rbf) and Random Forest.
  8. Boosting on the other hand, AdaBoosting showed an increase in performance of all the models with a greater increase in Naive Bayes and Decision Tree.
  9. Gradient Boosting showed a significant increase in accuracy of the decision tree.
  10. Gradient Boosting showed the highest accuracy in testing test with learning rates of 0.05 and 0.1
  11. SVM(rbf) algorithm provides one of the best accuracies of 89.35% but Decision Trees and Random Forests turned out to be the most accurate algorithms (89.45%) for the given scenario. Also, the high stability in the Random Forest algorithm ensures consistent result in the future unseen data.

Regularizations¶

  1. We tuned different values for K in KNN algorithm and found the optimal k at 20 giving 88.50% accuracy.
  2. In support vector machine we tested the different kernels available such as rbf which is default, linear and sigmoid kernels.
  3. rbf kernel gave the highest accuracy of (89.31%) followed by linear (88.24%) and sigmoid (81%).
  4. In decision tree we used the "entropy" and "gini" as the parameter index with gini giving a slightly lesser accuracy by 0.14%.
  5. An unregularized Decision Tree gave a testing accuracy of 99.99% but failed miserably on training set. This happened due to overfitting in the model.
  6. Also, with testing of different values of max_depth, we found that max_depth of 5 gave the optimum accuracy of 89.27%.
  7. In random forest, we tested with different number of estimators and with 50 estimators we got an accuracy of 89.25 %.
  8. In AdaBoosting, learning rate of 1 with logistic regression gave the maximum accuracy of 88.8% whereas a learning rate of 0.05 gave the maximum accuracy of 88.1% in Naive Bayes.
  9. Decision tree on the other hand used learning rate of 0.05 to achieve a 89.53 % accuracy.
  10. We tested Gradient boosting with different learning rates on 50 estimators with random state of 5 to give the maximum accuracies of a 89.49% for the learning rates of 0.05 and 0.1

Recommendations¶

  1. Therefore with the above inferences we can conclude that the bank should focus more on the low and medium balance groups within age bracket between 40-60.
  2. Also, married and divorcee customers should be targetted more than the single customers.
  3. The bank should focus and target its customers in the month of march which provides the highest success rate and prevent making calls in december which shows very less people subscribing to the deposits.
  4. The bank should prepare a questionare before making calls as the duration is one of the most important factors in a customer subscribing to a term deposit.
  5. The bank should make no more than 5-6 calls per client as this would save time and effort which can be directed towards contacting more potential customers thereby covering a larger customer base and increasing subscription ratio.
  6. The bank should therefore use ensemble models such as Random Forests to get a stable and highly accurate result in classifying the potential customers for subscribing the security term-deposits in future campaigns.
